Hey, no sweat Idontwantthis, I know way too well how easy it is for life to get in the way. Shit, man. It took me months to get through a single night's worth of story line. As I mentioned in my first comment,
>>18793770
It's not that it was a bad story - it was more that it started out with an oops (not a bad way to go. Lots of journey type stories start with something small the main(s) do, that kicks off more serious fallout and drives the rest of the story.

There were two issues I took with the story. The first one, and probably what bothered me the most, was that Kate and Ken were both effectively passive characters in their own story. When the condom broke, both characters went into full panic, then proceeded to do nothing about it until they flashed forward to the pregnancy test. Questions abound about why they didn't get Plan-B, or why Kate didn't go to her Gyn. to see if there was anything she could do (I suppose this could always be addressed later). They also have a bit of a depressing relationship to start with, as Ken seems to be a bit of a plan nothing, chase nothing, take things as they come sort of guy, and Kate as equal parts victim and hen-pecking / emasculating partner. I've seen this game play out in reality land before, and it's as painful to watch there as it is to watch here.

The other thing that kinda bothered be was the consistent lows without much in the way of highs. Both characters spend about 80% of the story despairing about the future, and in the other 20% one will drag the other back into the downward spiral. Again, I've seen similar things back in reality land, more often than not with the relationship cratering.

I'm definitely not saying that this isn't a valid take, nor is it a 'wrong' direction to take a story.
